  <p>
    For the full list of INPS contribution codes and their meanings, consult the <a href="https://www.inps.it/it/it/dettaglio-scheda.schede-servizio-strumento.schede-servizi.contributi-previdenziali-lavoratori-dipendenti-702.contributi-previdenziali-lavoratori-dipendenti.html" class="text-brand hover:underline">INPS contribution reference page</a>. For IRPEF bracket details and deduction formulas, refer to the <a href="https://www.agenziaentrate.gov.it/portale/web/guest/irpef" class="text-brand hover:underline">Agenzia delle Entrate IRPEF guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="red-flags-to-watch-for">Red Flags to Watch For</h2>

  <p>
    Payslip errors are more common than you might think, and they can cost you hundreds or even thousands of euros per year if left unchecked. Here is a checklist of the most important things to verify each month when you receive your busta paga.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>1. Verify your INPS contributions are correct.</strong> The employee contribution rate for most private-sector workers is <strong>9.19%</strong> of gross pay (as set by <a href="https://www.inps.it/it/it/dettaglio-scheda.schede-servizio-strumento.schede-servizi.contributi-previdenziali-lavoratori-dipendenti-702.contributi-previdenziali-lavoratori-dipendenti.html" class="text-brand hover:underline">INPS regulations</a>). Multiply your <em>imponibile previdenziale</em> (INPS taxable base) by 9.19% and compare the result with the amount shown on your payslip. If it does not match, there may be a calculation error or an incorrectly applied rate. For example, if your gross pay is &euro;2,308 and the INPS deduction shown is &euro;180 instead of the expected &euro;212, you are being undercharged &mdash; which sounds positive but could result in gaps in your pension record.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>2. Check your CCNL level (livello) and base pay (minimo tabellare).</strong> Your contract specifies a CCNL level (e.g., CCNL Commercio Livello 3, CCNL Metalmeccanico Livello D1). Each level has a minimum base pay set by the national agreement. If your <em>paga base</em> is lower than the CCNL minimum for your level, your employer is underpaying you. You can find current CCNL pay tables on the <a href="https://www.gazzettaufficiale.it/" class="text-brand hover:underline">Gazzetta Ufficiale</a> website or through your trade union. For instance, the CCNL Commercio Level 3 minimum for 2026 is approximately &euro;1,718/month (14 payments): if your payslip shows a lower figure and no superminimo makes up the difference, flag it immediately.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>3. Confirm overtime hours are counted correctly.</strong> Compare the <em>ore straordinario</em> (overtime hours) shown on the payslip with your own records. Many workers track overtime informally but neglect to verify it appears on the payslip. Under most CCNLs, overtime is paid at premiums of 15% (first 8 hours per week), 20% (next hours), and 30% (Sundays and holidays) above the normal hourly rate. Missing or under-reported overtime directly reduces your gross pay. If you work in a company with an electronic time-tracking system (<em>rilevazione presenze</em>), you should periodically cross-check your badge records against payslip data.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>4. Is your TFR accruing properly?</strong> Your TFR (Trattamento di Fine Rapporto, or severance indemnity) should accrue at a rate of approximately one month's gross salary per year of service (specifically, annual gross / 13.5, plus an annual revaluation). Check the <em>TFR maturato</em> field in the summary footer of your payslip. If you have been employed for 3 full years and your RAL is &euro;30,000, your TFR should be approximately &euro;6,667 plus revaluations (roughly &euro;7,000+ with ISTAT adjustments). If the figure is significantly lower, your employer may have made errors in the accrual or may not have applied the annual ISTAT revaluation (rivalutazione) correctly. The TFR calculation rules are defined in <a href="https://www.normattiva.it/uri-res/N2Ls?urn:nir:stato:codice.civile:1942-03-16;262" class="text-brand hover:underline">Art. 2120 of the Italian Civil Code</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>5. Review regional and municipal surcharges.</strong> These surcharges (<em>addizionali</em>) vary by where you are officially resident, not where you work. If you moved to a different municipality or region during the year, ensure your payroll office has updated your residency. Being charged the wrong regional rate (for example, Lazio at 3.33% instead of Lombardy at 1.73% on the same bracket) can mean an overcharge of hundreds of euros annually. Verify the rates on the <a href="https://www.agenziaentrate.gov.it/portale/web/guest/addizionali-comunali" class="text-brand hover:underline">Agenzia delle Entrate addizionali page</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>6. Confirm your remaining leave balance.</strong> Check the <em>ferie residue</em> (remaining vacation days) and <em>permessi residui</em> (remaining ROL hours) figures. Errors here may indicate that holiday days were deducted when you were actually working, or that accrued leave was not correctly carried forward from the previous year.
  </p>

